data: He is charged with culpable homicide, not amounting to murder. Qureshi said that 22 of the 74 people killed were his relatives.
He is charged with culpable homicide, not amounting to murder.
Chavan was suspended from active duty for his role in the affair. He was apparently paid 500000 () for his final approval of the project.
Sayyed is said to have been paid 4,000 for having arranged a meeting with Senior Inspector K. Naik and bribing police officers. The investigation will continue to determine who was bribed.
Money was delivered to Andhale by Dawood Kamdar.
Hira Patil, pulled into the case by Jabbar Patel, was paid 500,000 to co-ordinate co-operation with senior municipal officials in Thane and Kisna Madke.
Ansari supplied low cost building material.

According to police, Patel connected the builders with Diaghar policemen to arrange for a no-objection certificate. He requested a meeting with senior officials was arranged through Diaghar officer Sayeed and he contacted Afroz Ansari for low cost building material.
Madke was paid 500,000 to introduce Babasaheb Andhale to the developers.
Called the "fake architect", he has no degree in architecture but created the building plan. On the date of arrest he was 59.
A local journalist, he is suspected of co-ordinating the bribes of local officials and police for the builders; His name was found in one of the builder's diary. On the date of arrest he was 44.
Executive Engineer, responsible for removing illegal construction

Rawal is one of the "two top Thane municipal corporation engineers" charged with dereliction of duty. According to a senior police official, the engineers accepted bribes. Doing so, they did not conduct their assigned duties to remove encroached buildings.
Deputy Engineer, responsible for removing illegal construction
Inamdar is the other engineer charged with dereliction of duty.
Thorbole was arrested for taking bribes of 100,000 related to illegal housing on 23 January 2013 and later suspended. He was arrested 11 April for taking a bribe to stop the demolition drive.
The Thane Police crime Branch Choudhary, also called "Uncle", was arrested by the crime branch of the Thane Police on 12 April 2013. He was a partner of the developer of the collapsed building.
Waghmare's name figured in the diary of builder Jameel Qureshi who bribed civic officials to overlook violations in the construction of the seven-storey building.
Burud would regularly demand money from Qureshi who maintained a record of the cash paid to the officials.

table-1262-399.pgTitle: List of tornadoes in the April 25–28, 2011 tornado outbreak (Part 2)
table-1262-399.caption: April 28 event
data: Four homes were either heavily damaged or destroyed due to falling trees.
Hundreds of trees were downed, several of which damaged eight structures.
Numerous trees were knocked down along the path.

Tornado injured two people and tore roofs off barns and homes, tossed a half-ton piece of industrial equipment 200 yards, and leveled an agricultural chicken building down to the foundation. One mobile home was destroyed as well.
Several homes damaged and outbuildings destroyed. Trees were snapped and uprooted.
Numerous large trees uprooted near a horse farm.
Several trees snapped or uprooted. The roof was removed from a barn and a house had minor roof damage.
Numerous trees were downed. A tree fell on a house causing minor roof damage.
A double-wide manufactured home was mostly destroyed, along with small sheds and outbuildings. Multiple homes sustained roof damage and there was one minor injury.

A shed that housed a sawmill was totally destroyed and a residence had a portion of its roof removed with parts of a porch blown over the house. Significant damage was also noted at a farmstead. A mobile home was pushed off of its foundation and multiple barns and outbuildings were destroyed.
A portion of a hog farm was destroyed and its debris was scattered for several hundred yards. Multiple trees were snapped and uprooted.
The roof of an upholstery shop was ripped. A shed was damaged, along with a dozen trees.
Extreme damage occurred to two grain silos, and a barn was blown across a road. Trees in the area were snapped and uprooted.
Minor damage occurred to three homes in the area. Numerous trees were snapped and uprooted.
Trees and power lines were downed along Bell Town Road.
Touched down in an open field where there was no damage.
Tornado slammed into a turkey house, causing significant damage and killing a number of turkeys.

A well-constructed barn, a garage, and a mobile home were destroyed. An 11,000-pound camper was flipped up and over a five-foot fence. A home had its windows blown out, with debris found impaled into its siding and yard. Two horses were killed.

One home had roof and wall damage, while another home sustained roof and window damage. In addition, a metal outbuilding completely collapsed, and a barn's roof was damaged. A tree branch was found impaled through a car's windshield. The storm went on to produce straight-line wind damage of a similar intensity for another 1.7 miles, damaging two more homes.
A house trailer, outbuildings and a two-story barn were destroyed. A jeep was moved several feet, and water was sucked out of a pond.
A couple of homes were damaged along with numerous trees.
Several houses sustained structural damage and trees were uprooted.
Damage mostly to trees. One tree caused damage to a home.
Several trees uprooted along Marshall Mill Road and Mt. Carmel Road.
Two dozen trees were uprooted in a heavily wooded area.
Tornado snapped and uprooted several trees, caused minor home damage and destroyed outbuildings in the town of Breton Bay. Tornado crossed Breton Bay and lifted just east of Leonardtown.
Minor damage to two homes. One home was damaged by a tree.

Tornado ripped a roof off an apartment house, threw debris into a car dealership across the street damaging vehicles on the lot. Nearby homes sustained roof damage. A back porch was ripped from a home and thrown a half-block away. Trees were also uprooted. The tornado was on the ground for 2 to 3 minutes.

Four homes were damaged, two moderately. One barn was destroyed, two others damaged. One farm outbuilding was destroyed, two others damaged along with a silo. Two high tension electricity towers were toppled. About 200 trees were knocked down. A cow was injured.
Tornado touched down along an intermittent 11-mile long path. Numerous trees were snapped, and large tree limbs were found on roofs of homes.
Brief tornado touchdown, with trees down.

title: Trog Seose, My Chree / Rise Up, My Heart
Trog Seose, My Chree / Rise Up, My Heart
table-1262-10.caption: Carvals
data: Trog seose, my chree, nagh mie dhyts nish, Dty aigney slane hyndaa, Voish shelg lurg nhee aghyn faase y theihll Nagh vel agh myr veeagh kay. Ayns geiyrtys er tou goll rishyn, Ta oaggey nei yn gheay, Ny marrinee gleck noi geay as muir, Ta ooilley slane ny oie. Te myr veagh tonn jeh'n faarkey quaagh, Lesh sterrym goll heose as sheese, Shen myr ta mish fud boirey'n theihll Cha vel aym laa dy aash.

Rise up, my heart! 'tis well for thee To turn thyself wholly From following weak worldly things, Which as a vapour pass. In following these thou'rt like to him Who fights against the winds, Or sailors wrestling all the night Against the stormy sea. Just like a wave in a rough sea, With storms heaves up and down, So I, midst troubles of this world, Have not a day of rest.

data: Julie is over the moon when Nathan is scheduled to return home, but when Ted doesn't show up, Dave has to go get him from the airport. The new sparky - and Frankie's old friend - Buzz who takes an immediate liking to Emma. Donna decides to hire Craig again for the night. Craig runs into Emma and begins juggling Donna and Emma - mother and daughter. Ted returns to his old house and reunites with ex-lover Eleanor McCormack. Carbo, Retta and Emma are having trouble with their shop and they decide to take out an ad in Julie's newspaper. Narrated by: Julie Rafter

Nathan is working hard to build a solid base for Saskia & Edward in Australia and accepts a job offer despite its obvious shortfalls. Saskia is excited to be joining him, but little does Nathan know, for the first time in their married life, Saskia is keeping something from him. Meanwhile, Emma is quietly giddy at the prospect of her blossoming romance with Craig. Narrated by: Nathan Rafter

When new employee Buzz brings his wayward son Jackson to a work site, Dave begins to suspect his good nature is being taken advantage of. Meanwhile, Donna is mortified when she learns that both she and Emma have been played by Craig. Donna tries to avoid telling Emma, but she can't hide the truth forever, setting up an impending confrontation like no other. Narrated by: Dave Rafter

An exhausted Nathan arrives in London looking for Saskia and baby Edward, desperate to find out why his wife never arrived in Sydney as planned, and the answer changes his life forever. Back in Sydney, Julie's concern for Nathan is exacerbated by Ted's continuing decline, which is clearly accelerating when Julie witnesses him confusing Eleanor for her mother. Narrated by: Nathan Rafter

Narrated by: Ted Taylor

And when Carbo discovers she's been lying to him over something as fundamental as having a child, its shaping up to be one hell of a party... Narrated by: Carbo Karandonis

Dave's enduring belief that nothing is beyond repair is put to the test when a crisis envelops the Rafter family. Frankie visits Coby in prison and after some initial awkwardness, they fall back into their usual, easy banter. But any hope Frankie has about their future is sidelined when she discovers that someone else has feelings for her. Having had no contact from Buzz, Emma is left wondering if she know that Buzz is actually paralysed by his feelings for Emma. Narrated by: Dave Rafter

Julie and Dave raise the difficult topic of nursing homes with Ted, and while he initially digs his heels in, a potentially serious accident forces him to acknowledge that hes becoming a danger to himself and others. Frankie is juggling a visit from older sister Carla and once again, unresolved family issues loom large. After an intense build-up, Buzz and Emma finally get together, but when Buzz is surprised by something he finds in Jackson's schoolbag, he realises he has no idea how to juggle being a dad with a new relationship. Narrated by: Julie Rafter

It's a matter of head versus heart as Julie and Dave wrestle with their decision to sell their beloved family home. When push comes to shove will they be able to go through with it? Jackson, miserable living with his mum and her new boyfriend, fishes to move in with Buzz. Matt, in the middle of a drought, has a lucky break - an invite to record some songs with a band. Unfortunately, nerves get the better of him and he blows his big chance. Frankie comes to the rescue with a surprising solution and Matt's drought is finally broken, in more ways than one... Narrated by: Dave Rafter

Sammy returns and her and Nathan plan to raise Edward as friends. Julie and Dave decide to rent a house instead of buy one. Retta discovers that - despite being on the pill - she is pregnant. Narrated by: Julie Rafter

table-1262-617.caption: Tournament History
data: Kyoto, Osaka and Kobe For the first tournament, as the main schedule was designed to follow the fiscal year, the winter tournament schedule was designed right after the autumn tournament (so the order was to be summer → autumn → winter, but owing to a problem with participant transportation the winter tournament did not take place). This was similar schedule to the pre-war Meiji Shrine tournament. Owing to this, in the second tournament, from where a calendar system was used, there was no winter tournament. From the third tournament, the winter tournament came into action, giving the tournament order of winter → summer → autumn.

table-1262-393.pgTitle: List of tornadoes in the April 25–28, 2011 tornado outbreak (Part 1)
table-1262-393.caption: April 26 event
data: Trees were uprooted and snapped and a metal frame building was crushed. Several buildings sustained roof damage.
Tornado snapped and uprooted trees. Several homes sustained roof damage and a carport was destroyed. Multiple barns were destroyed and power poles were downed.
Tornado was miles (m) wide at its peak. Fifteen homes had major roof damage and many trees were snapped and uprooted.
Short-lived tornado downed trees and power lines.
Very brief and weak tornado downed a few trees.
Tornado caused damage at the Hardin County Fairgrounds.
Tree limbs downed and signs damaged.
Three mobile homes destroyed and 100 homes damaged by the tornado. Trees were downed and a church also sustained damage.
Trees were downed at a golf course.
Trees were downed along the path.
A barn was destroyed and a house was damaged. Numerous trees were downed as well.
Three houses was damaged and trees were downed.
Several buildings were damaged downtown. The steeple was torn off a church and cars and windows were damaged by flying debris. Trees and power poles were downed as well.

Long-lived wedge tornado was mostly weak during its track but briefly intensified to EF2 and reached miles (km) in width, resulting in significant damage and two injuries. Many trees and power poles were snapped, and homes were damaged to varying degrees along the path. Barns were also destroyed and a trailer was flipped over.
Brief tornado with minor tree damage.
Numerous trees were snapped and uprooted.
Small rope tornado reported with minor tree damage.
A rain-wrapped tornado caused minor tree damage.

Tornado snapped or uprooted several trees. One barn was destroyed with debris being thrown over yards (m) and another barn was damaged. Several homes received roof damage and three power poles were snapped.
Numerous trees were snapped at the base and several more were uprooted. A barn was damaged with debris being carried yards (m) and a small building was destroyed.
Several houses were damaged, one of which sustained major roof damage. A carport and a playground were destroyed.
Trees and power lines were knocked down and one home was damaged.
Tornado touched down in a wooded area and downed numerous trees.

Damage at an athletic field near a school where bleachers were blown away. A press box was thrown from its supports, metal poles were broken, and soccer goals were bent. Tree damage also occurred and a portable toilet was thrown miles (km).

Multiple trees were uprooted and the roof was torn from a warehouse building. Trailers were overturned and multiple cars had their windows blown out. Several barns and turkey houses had were damaged or destroyed. One house received minor roof and garage-door damage.
Tornado yards (m) wide snapped trees and caused minor damage to buildings.

Two grain bins destroyed and the roof was torn from a farm shop. A tractor trailer was overturned and irrigation pivots were flipped. Multiple trees and power poles were snapped, some of which landed on homes.
A brief tornado touched down in an open field with no damage.
A church suffered roof damage and several trees snapped or uprooted. A few irrigation systems were damaged as well.
Trees were blown down and there was roof damage to several homes.
Brief landspout tornado that touched down in an agricultural area. No damage was reported.
Numerous trees were snapped and uprooted and several homes sustained roof damage.
Six houses sustained minor damage and several trees were downed; most of this occurred in Lawson.
Trees and power poles were knocked down.
Numerous trees were snapped and uprooted.
Minor roof damage to a few homes, downed trees.
A few structures suffered roof damage and trees were downed.
Low-end EF1 tornado destroyed two barns, caused roof damage to several houses, and downed several trees.
Several trees were knocked down and the tin roof on a home was peeled back.
Sources: SPC Storm Reports for 04/26/11, NWS Jackson, MS, NWS Little Rock, NWS Dallas/Fort Worth NWS Louisville, NWS Paducah, NWS Norman, NWS Shreveport, NWS Northern Indiana
